  "prompt": "Relation between change in celcius to change in fahrenhiet?",
  "response": "The relationship between a change in Celsius (\u00b0C) and a change in Fahrenheit (\u00b0F) is straightforward and proportional. Here's how they are related:\n\n1. Conversion Formula:\n   Change in Fahrenheit = (Change in Celsius) \u00d7 9/5\n   or\n   \u0394F = (\u0394C) \u00d7 9/5\n\n2. Key Points:\n   - A change of 1\u00b0C is equal to a change of 1.8\u00b0F\n   - For every 1 degree change in Celsius, the Fahrenheit scale changes by 1.8 degrees\n\n3. Examples:\n   - If temperature increases by 10\u00b0C, it will increase by 18\u00b0F\n   - If temperature decreases by 5\u00b0C, it will decrease by 9\u00b0F\n\n4. Calculation:\n   \u0394F = \u0394C \u00d7 9/5\n   or\n   \u0394C = \u0394F \u00d7 5/9\n\nThis relationship is consistent regardless of the starting temperature, making it easy to convert temperature changes between the two scales.",
